-Types of Relations
1)Empty Relation 
-∅

2)Full Relation 
-X×Y

3)Identity Relation
-{(x,x)|x∈X}

4)Inverse Relation 
-R′={(b,a)|(a,b)∈R}

-Examples 
-If R={(1,2),(2,3)} then R′ will be {(2,1),(3,2)}

4)Reflexive Relation
-if ∀a∈A is related to a (aRa holds)
-R={(a,a),(b,b)} on set X={a,b} is reflexive.

4)Irreflexive Relation
-if no a∈A is related to a (aRa does not hold).
-R={(a,b),(b,a)} on set X={a,b} is irreflexive.

-Symmetric Relation
-if xRy implies yRx, ∀x∈A and ∀y∈A.
-R={(1,2),(2,1),(3,2),(2,3)} on set A={1,2,3} is symmetric.

-Anti-Symmetric Relation 
-if xRy and yRx implies x=y∀x∈A and ∀y∈A.
-R={(x,y)→N|x≤y} is anti-symmetric since x≤y and y≤x implies x=y.

-Transitive Relation 
-if xRy and yRz implies xRz,∀x,y,z∈A.
-R={(1,2),(2,3),(1,3)} on set A={1,2,3} is transitive.

-Equivalence Relation 
-if it is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
-R={(1,1),(2,2),(3,3),(1,2),(2,1),(2,3),(3,2),(1,3),(3,1)} on set A={1,2,3}















